{
  "query": "What are the documented effects on farmland biodiversity of switching from mineral to organic fertilizers?",
  "relevant_summary": "The documented effects show that switching from mineral to organic fertilizers consistently supports higher farmland biodiversity. Fourteen studies from Austria, Belgium, Germany, Ireland, Switzerland and the UK found that organic fertilizer applications increased plant diversity and cover, earthworm abundance, diversity, biomass and density, and abundance and/or species richness of some or all invertebrate groups investigated. One literature review specifically found that organic fertilizers without pesticides produced the highest earthworm biomass, while a study in Belgium found more predatory beetles on arable fields two years after organic fertilizer application than on control plots. Additionally, a replicated, randomized, controlled study from Italy found more plants and plant biomass in plots with organic fertilizer compared to inorganic fertilizer.\n\nHowever, some studies found limited or no effects. One UK trial found organic fertilizers did not affect the abundance of three weed species, an Irish study found farmyard manure had no long-term effects on invertebrates, and two UK studies found increases in arthropod predators and springtails were only seen at a local, not field scale. One review also reported that heavy applications of slurry can be toxic to common earthworms.",
