{
  "query": "As an alternative to conventional ploughing, what are the wildlife benefits of undersowing spring cereals?",
  "relevant_summary": "Undersowing spring cereals provides significant wildlife benefits compared to conventional ploughing practices. Fifteen studies from the UK, Austria, Denmark, Finland and Switzerland found that undersowing spring cereals benefited birds, plants, insects, spiders and earthworms. Specific benefits included increases in barnacle goose abundance, densities of singing Eurasian skylark and nesting dunnock, arthropod abundance and species richness, and bumblebee, butterfly, earthworm, ground beetle, spider or springtail abundances. Two studies specifically on butterflies and moths found that undersown spring cereals had higher species richness and abundance of butterflies compared to extensively or conventionally managed grassland. Three studies found higher densities of some bird species on undersown fields, though not all species showed this preference. While five studies found that undersowing did not benefit certain species including grey partridge, invertebrates, or some farmland birds, the overall evidence demonstrates that undersowing spring cereals as an alternative to conventional ploughing provides substantial benefits to a wide range of farmland wildlife including birds, pollinators, and soil organisms.",
